{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17641906","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17641906"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:33:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:33:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17916"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17916","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17916"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10630"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72815"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10630","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10630"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17916"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58285"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8126"},{"type":"tags","id":"10069"},{"type":"tags","id":"10770"},{"type":"tags","id":"11243"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24765"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24768"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72815","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72815"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following mechanisms is most likely contributing to insulin resistance in a type 2 diabetes patient\u0027s liver?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Production of mitochondrial nitric oxide due to excessive beta oxidation of fatty acids","Stress signals from endoplasmic reticulum due to loading of unfolded proteins","Increase in ceramides which activate Akt","Inflammatory signaling activating insulin receptor substrate proteins","Accumulation of diacylglycerol activating protein kinase C"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn the context of insulin resistance, the liver often accumulates lipids, leading to the production of \u003Cstrong\u003Ediacylglycerol (DAG)\u003C/strong\u003E. DAG activates protein kinase C (PKC), which in turn impairs insulin signaling by inhibiting insulin receptor substrate (IRS) proteins. This mechanism is a key contributor to hepatic insulin resistance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduction of mitochondrial nitric oxide\u003C/strong\u003E due to excessive beta oxidation of fatty acids is not a primary mechanism of insulin resistance in the liver. While mitochondrial dysfunction can contribute to metabolic disturbances, it is not directly linked to insulin resistance through this pathway.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncrease in ceramides\u003C/strong\u003E can interfere with insulin signaling, but they do not activate Akt. Instead, ceramides are more commonly associated with the inhibition of Akt, which would impair insulin signaling rather than enhance it.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInflammatory signaling\u003C/strong\u003E can contribute to insulin resistance by interfering with IRS proteins, but the primary mechanism in the liver involves DAG and PKC activation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStress signals from the endoplasmic reticulum\u003C/strong\u003E due to the loading of unfolded proteins can contribute to insulin resistance, but this is not the primary mechanism in the liver. Endoplasmic reticulum stress is more commonly associated with systemic insulin resistance and metabolic syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Insulin resistance in the liver is associated with the accumulation of diacylglycerol (DAG), which activates protein kinase C (PKC) and impairs insulin signaling.","Inflammatory signaling and endoplasmic reticulum stress can contribute to insulin resistance by interfering with insulin receptor substrate (IRS) proteins."],"references":["Bender, D. A., \u0026 Cunningham, S. M. (2021). Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press","Salway, J. G. (2016). Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Banday MZ, Sameer AS, Nissar S. Pathophysiology of diabetes: An overview. Avicenna J Med. 2020 Oct 13;10(4):174-188. doi: 10.4103/ajm.ajm_53_20. PMID: 33437689; PMCID: PMC7791288","Galicia-Garcia U, Benito-Vicente A, Jebari S, Larrea-Sebal A, Siddiqi H, Uribe KB, Ostolaza H, Mart\u00edn C. Pathophysiology of Type 2 Diabetes Mellitus. Int J Mol Sci. 2020 Aug 30;21(17):6275. doi: 10.3390/ijms21176275. PMID: 32872570; PMCID: PMC7503727","Banday MZ, Sameer AS, Nissar S. Pathophysiology of diabetes: An overview. Avicenna J Med. 2020 Oct 13;10(4):174-188. doi: 10.4103/ajm.ajm_53_20. PMID: 33437689; PMCID: PMC7791288"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58285"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17916"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58285","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58285"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-22T08:44:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-22T08:45:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10630"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72815"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","n